      "year": 2022,
      "abstract": "Paolo Sandro\u2019s book is the latest volume in Hart Publishing\u2019s excellent \u2018Law and Practical Reason\u2019 series. The book\u2019s theoretical scope is wide, engaging with analytical legal philosophy (of both Anglo-American and continental varieties), constitutional theory, philosophy of language, and continental administrative law. It will be of interest to scholars in each of these disciplines and others besides. A consistent through line, uniting these variegated elements, is the claim that there is a conceptual distinction between the creation of law and its application, and that this distinction is vital for legal and constitutional theory. Sandro argues that two unfortunate conclusions would follow from the theoretical breakdown of the distinction between law creation and application. First, law would lose its capacity to solve coordination problems and guide action; a function that Sandro considers a key part of the concept of law (17). Secondly, it would entail that legal practice is anti-democratic, as it would follow that law is not, as we generally suppose it is, made by our elected representatives (2). A conceptual distinction between law creation and application, then, is a necessary legitimacy condition of constitutional democracies. Framing the debate in this way comes with limitations. The claim, in essence, is that if we don\u2019t accept the creation/application distinction, then law is not legitimate in the way that we think it is. But Sandro\u2019s main interlocutors \u2013 legal realists of classical and modern stripes \u2013 would be perfectly happy to accept this conclusion. They may even respond, \u2018yes, precisely\u2019. It isn\u2019t clear, then, that Sandro succeeds in talking to his targets and not past them, but we can leave this to the realists to decide. We can still take these claims seriously on their own terms. As mentioned, one of the book\u2019s great contributions is the staging of scholarly encounters between theorists from multiple theoretical backgrounds and disciplines. A critique of Hobbes is held up alongside engagement with Kojin Karatani\u2019s analysis of \u2018isonomia\u2019. Familiar general jurisprudential debates on judicial \u2018discretion\u2019 are viewed through the lens of traditions of administrative discretion in Germany, Italy and France. And various continental constitutional theorists are given a prominence that is often unjustifiably denied to them in Anglophone literature. This is an ambitious project, in other words, and almost any reader who is expert in one particular area with which Sandro engages is likely to be rewarded with an encounter between their own discipline and some less familiar one. This alone makes it a welcome addition to the constitutional theory canon, broadly defined. While the breadth of the book\u2019s scope is undoubtedly a boon, it does, as other reviewers have noted, make it rather difficult to summarise the book or to do justice to all its arguments. I will therefore offer only a brief outline of the book\u2019s structure, before focussing",
